data.message: Hello TSP members! Many thanks to those of you who have done our first follow-up survey sent out two weeks ago. For those of you who haven't, don't forget to check your email and complete it for a $20 gift card! You’ll earn an additional $20 at the end if you fill out all surveys!

Just a friendly reminder to check your email and fill out the first follow-up survey that we sent out last week. Remember, you'll receive $20 for completing it and will receive an additional $20 at the end if you complete all follow-up surveys!
Hey TSP members! We apologize for the slight delay in sending out gift cards for your comments. We'll be sure to get them to you this week, so keep an eye on your inbox! Thanks for your patience :)

Hello TSP members! Yesterday's post concludes our 90-day program. Please check your email this week for our first follow-up survey. You will receive a $20 gift card upon completion.We hope that our Facebook group has been enjoyable, educational, and life-changing in some way, whether it be a shift in your perspective towards smoking, or a commitment towards a healthier, smoke-free life. All of us at TSP have enjoyed reading your comments and interacting with you online, and we truly thank you for your participation.Although we will no longer be posting daily, you are welcome to remain in this secret group and access all of the content we've shared over the past 90 days. Furthermore, we're still available to answer any questions/concerns about smoking, and we're open to any feedback/suggestions you may have for our program.Again, from all of us at TSP, thank you and good luck in your future endeavors!
is there another start for any surveys if I have a friend who wants to join?

Have you ever noticed a connection between smoking and your mood? Is there an emotional state that gets you to light up more frequently? #TDII

Hi 10333 - yes that's a common one. Have you already tried some of the stress reduction techniques we have covered in TSP? If so how did it go?
i played on my phone a lot and it really helped get my mind off it. i havenet bought a pack since my quit date but its been hard!
Great job 10333 - you can be proud of yourself - smokefree since Saturday :)
Sounds like playing on your phone works well for now. What else have you tried to take your mind off?
ive had headaches everyday tho :( and i listen to music too
Headaches can be rough - I hear you 10333. Hang in there! The thing to look forward to is that the withdrawal will only get better from here. Check out these quick fixes - anything sound useful?
Also check out these benefits 10333
i can't wait for that 15 year mark!!!! these headaches are pretty terrible. and nothing helps

And you are on your way to that mark 10333. Take it one day at a time for now! Sorry to hear about your headaches. The only thing I can say is that they WILL get better over time. Soon you'll wake up and feel great - just hang in there for now!

watching funny videos and playing phone games

10382 that is ok! it is a good idea to spend sometime though, thinking and reflecting on a safe, healthy, outlet for stress. For example, taking a walk, calling a friend on the phone, meeting someone for coffee, or just taking a nice hot shower! Talking in this group can also be a safe space to talk about any stress you may be feeling.

data.description: Hi everyone and welcome to the group. On Wednesday, I will be holding the first "The Doctor Is In" session from 5-6 PM (Pacific Time). You can ask me everything you want to know around smoking, quitting, and the Tobacco Status Project.

data.message: Hey TSP members! We have decided to postpone our start date to this Friday. We apologize for the delay. Thanks for your patience and sit tight for two more days! :)

Welcome to the Tobacco Status Project! Thank you for joining us -- we're so excited to have you here. We will start posting TOMORROW at 12 noon PST! Here's how it works:We will share one post everyday for 90 days. Remember to turn on your notifications and check this page daily!Your group has been randomly assigned to a Monthly Incentive. To earn money, you must comment on ALL posts we share each month (30 days). You will earn $30 if you've commented on all 30 posts, and $0 if you haven't. We'll tally your comments every 30 days, and you'll have a new chance to earn money at the start of the next month. You will receive a gift card for the money you've earned at the end of the 90-day program.Dr. Johannes Thrul will be joining us for 1 hour each week, during which he will answer any tobacco-related questions, share info and resources, and provide support to our group. Stay tuned for his first session next week!
Thank you! Very excited to start this.

Hello TSP members! While we wait for more people to join us, we want you to know that this secret group is a great place to share your thoughts and engage in conversation. Please feel free to like or respond to each others' comments and share any relevant content of your own.Let's take a moment to introduce ourselves and get to know each other a little better. Feel free to share with us:• Where you come from• Anything about your smoking (how much, how often, when you first started, etc.)• What you hope to gain from participating in the Tobacco Study ProjectThank you! We hope you're as excited as we are!

Hey group members! Our secret group is still growing, but the TSP program will be starting soon. Double check your notifications for this page and make sure they’re turned on (click “Notifications” in the upper right hand corner). Who's ready to get this show on the road?!

Welcome to the Tobacco Study Project! We're so happy that you’re joining us and can't wait to start. We're still adding people to this secret group, but in the meantime feel free to look at our Consent Form and TSP Group Rules (click the "Files" link above). Thanks for your patience and stay tuned! :)

data.message: This group is for 18-25 year olds who currently smoke and are ready to quit in the very near future. While your quit-date approaches, get educated about Nicotine Replacement Therapies, ways to prepare for and deal with cravings & triggers, grow your support system and learn the best techniques to quit and STAY quit. This group has been randomly selected to have Monthly Incentives; you can accumulate $30 at the end of every month in which you comment every day, for a gift card of up to $90 at the end of the session.

Johannes Thrul created the event Session 3 - Smoking cessation advice.

data.message: Hi guys, I am getting ready to start with session 3. Stop by if you want to learn about social support and quitting.
Hi guys - I have posted the content of today's session on the wall of this event. Feel free to check it out!

That’s it for today’s session.Between now and next time, practice being assertive. You can do it!Also, keep commenting on your Daily Tracking of Smoking, Mood, and Activities. Use this Pleasant Activities checklist to identify some activities that interest you. See you next time! Bye.

Sometimes you may have to respond by revealing to others how their behavior/comments make you feel. There are 3 steps to being successful with this: 1. Be neutral when describing their behavior to them2. Use “I feel” statements to describe how you feel about their comments/behavior3. Let them know what you want from them (i.e. a specific behavior change) that can help you as you quitHow do you think you could use these 3 steps in your situations to respond assertively?

Although other people may not always change their behavior upon your request, using these steps gives you a better chance of getting what you want and will leave you feeling better about yourself and your ability to be assertive.
Everyone is not the same personality. There are many personal styles of communicating:First is the passive style. Here’s a list:
Next there’s the aggressive style:
There’s one last personality type—the ASSERTIVE type:

By being assertive, you have the best chance of getting what you want and you will feel better about yourself by stating/responding that way.BUT…being assertive does not mean that you always have to speak your mind in every situation.Are there any situations in your pursuit of quitting smoking where you guys would like to be more assertive?

How would you handle the following situations without smoking?2. You just got out of school. A bunch of your friends are hanging out on the side of the school.You watch as someone in the group pulls out a pack of your favorite cigarettes and lights up.You smell the smoke and think about how you always used to enjoy a cigarette after school.Your friend notices that you’re looking at the cigarette, holds out the pack says, “Want one?”What would you do or say?

How would you handle the following situations without smoking?1. You’re at a party with a group of friends. Your friends are smoking.You’re feeling relaxed and thinking about how you always used to smoke at parties.Just as you start to say to yourself, “A cigarette would sure be good now,” your friend offers you a cigarette.What would you do or say?

Think positively about your decision to refuse a cigarette.It is easy to go along with what everyone else is doing.You are someone who makes a decision to do something and sticks to it!Respect yourself, and you will earn the respect of others in the long run.Here’s a pic you can use to remind you of the tips
Here’s another tip: Respond confidently.
How can these tips work for you?

One of the biggest challenges for an ex-smoker is declining a cigarette offer. Developing and practicing effective ways to turn down cigarette offers will reduce the chances of getting caught off guard.What are some situations where you might be offered a cigarette?

Anticipating these things is the first step to effectively turning down a cigarette offer. The next step is to respond effectively.What are some things you could say in response to an offer in the situations you mentioned?
Today I thought I could talk a bit about "support" and quitting. Who is supportive about you quitting?

What are some things others can do that would be helpful to you while you become smoke-free? What can you ask them to do to support you?What are some things others can do that would NOT be helpful/hinder your quitting?And how can you ask your supporters to stop doing these unhelpful things?
How do you feel about your quitting now? Still feeling committed to staying smoke free?
If not, what barriers got in the way?
What triggers led you to smoke this week? What was your mood? Who were you with?
What do you think you can do differently next time you’re in a similar situation?
How did you use your mood log this week?
How many cigarettes did you smoke this week on average, number of pleasant activities, and your general mood? If you didn’t keep track, use your best guess.
Welcome to the third session. How has it been for you this week? When was the last time you smoked?
It's been better this week. I've cut back to two or three a day instead of eight to ten. My last one was this morning.
That's great 10382 - you are really trying hard to smoke less!

data.message: Remember what you are gaining by quitting.
i know! i didnt buy a pack today.... no more as of now!
Good luck!
Thank you!
First morning in a long time without my morning cigarette, So far so good!!!! (:

10333, all of us at TSP would like to wish you the BEST OF LUCK tomorrow! We all stand behind your decision to quit and hope that you will stick to it! So put out that last cigarette, take a deep breath, and get ready for positive change. We believe in you!
Thank you!
You've made your plan and prepared for what's ahead. On your Quit Day, remember to take things one day at a time. Slow and steady wins the race!
The night before your Quit Day, make sure you've gotten rid of all your cigarettes, lighters, matches and ashtrays from your car and home.
i dont smoke in my house my car will definitely need to be cleaned

The night before your Quit Day, put together a non-smoker survival kit, complete with sugarless gum/candy, toothpicks, other substitutes for smoking, a list of your reasons for quitting, and the phone numbers of your support people.
The night before your Quit Day, reflect on the fact that tomorrow will be your first day free from cigarette addiction!
After smoking your last cigarette the night before your Quit Day, take a shower, wash your hair, and brush your teeth. Get rid of all the last traces of nicotine!
better add laundry to that list
As your Quit Day approaches, we're going to share our "The Night Before Checklist" and "On Your Quit Day" series in this event. These are some final tips that we think are helpful :)
